name: 2-chloro-3-nitrobenzoic_acid
source: Aldrich Chemical Company; Aldrich Catalog-Handbook of Fine Chemicals; Milwaukee; WI; 1984.
Reason: The basic unit to consider is benzoic acid, which has a melting point of 122°C. When substituents are added to benzoic acid, the melting point can shift. The electron-withdrawing nitro group generally increases melting point due to its deactivating effect, increased molecular symmetry, and potential for intermolecular hydrogen bonding, which we can estimate as +40°C. The chlorine is also an electron-withdrawing group but to a lesser extent than the nitro group; it can contribute to an increase in melting point due to increased molecular mass and dipole moment. We might estimate this effect as +10°C. Together, these additions would predict an increase in the melting point. However, the specific arrangement of the groups on the benzene ring (ortho, meta, and para positions) can have important impacts on the melting behavior of the compound due to effects on molecular packing and potential intramolecular interactions, which could moderate the individual contributions of each group to the melting point.

name: 2-chloro-3-nitrobenzoic_acid
source: Aldrich Chemical Company; Aldrich Catalog-Handbook of Fine Chemicals; Milwaukee; WI; 1984.
Reason: The basic unit to consider here is benzoic acid, which has a melting point of 122°C. When adding substituents to the aromatic ring, the melting point can be affected. The nitro group, being a strong electron-withdrawing group and having the ability to partake in intermolecular hydrogen bonding, generally increases the melting point significantly. The increase might be around +50°C. The chloro group is also an electron-withdrawing group and contributes to the dipole moment and the molecular weight, which can further increase the melting point, but its effect is typically smaller than that of the nitro group. The increase due to the chloro group might be estimated at around +9°C. The combined effect of both substituents in the meta position relative to each other is expected to provide a significant but not additive increase due to potential steric hindrance and intramolecular interactions, conservatively estimated at +59°C combined.

name: 2-chloro-3-nitrobenzoic_acid
source: Aldrich Chemical Company; Aldrich Catalog-Handbook of Fine Chemicals; Milwaukee; WI; 1984.
Reason: Starting with the basic unit, benzene has a melting point of 5.5°C. The melting point is affected by the addition of functional groups as follows: The chloro group is an electron-withdrawing group and increases the melting point by approximately +40°C due to its inductive effect and potential for intermolecular interactions. The nitro group is also an electron-withdrawing group and increases the melting point significantly, about +80°C, due to its strong inductive effect and ability to form strong hydrogen bonds (as an acceptor). The carboxylic acid group increases the melting point by approximately +50°C because of its ability to form strong intermolecular hydrogen bonds and dimeric structures. The cumulative effect of these groups leads to an increased melting point.
